    <h3>Workshopping content layout</h3>
    <p>By this time, we had been working with several Foundations and experts who would be providing the smarts behind the Foundation Funds (choosing the best way to support a cause, selecting nonprofits). We found ourselves battling two extremes. We knew that most people give for emotional reasons. We don’t put in the same research as someone giving thousands or hundreds of thousands of dollars. At the same time, each Foundation Fund is based on sound, logical reasoning around a cause and the best way to support it. </p>
    <p>We wanted to speak to the emotional side without watering down the substance.</p>
    <p>At this point Bright Funds had been around for 4 years and the team had hundreds of conversations with donors to understand their experiences with giving. I held another round of calls with donors at this point as well. I then lead an exercise to layout out the flow of content. The goal here was to organize the content in a way that would capture someone’s attention and then speak to the internal questions someone asks themselves (often unknowingly) when deciding whether to give.</p>
    <img class="case-study__image" src="../images/cs-foundation-fund/content-order.jpg" alt="Sketch of content order">

    <h3>Imagine if...</h3>
    <p>The design of the Fund page mirrors the donor thought process we mapped earlier. I wanted to nudge people to think optimistically about a cause when they first land on a Foundation Fund page. This would engage emotional reasoning, which has been proven to be effective in encouraging donations. For this reason, each page starts with a series of ‘Imagine if…’ statements. “Imagine if every child had access to the healthcare they need”. Behind each statement is a related image that reiterates the emotional reasons to donate.</p>

  </div>

